segments.text: You'd go talk to him, particularly for his numbers.
He always had this old, humongous 1,000-key calculator, I guess.
I don't know.
And he would sit there.
Well, it was on this side because he was left-handed.
And he'd run some numbers, and he'd crunch numbers on that thing, and it would hum and whir and clank and everything, and he'd have the answer for you.
But no, Clark was a delight to work with.
In fact,
Really all the directors that I worked with were, we were, we had a really good group.
And a smooth relationship.
Yeah, a smooth relationship.
And also between Diebel and Cherry.
Yeah, oh yeah, yeah, yeah.
Now where was Howard Vestal at that time?
Howard Vestal was, then he was director of auxiliary enterprises.
Oh, okay.
You know, like the housing operations in the airport and
So that in those years, you didn't report through him?
No, no.
In fact, Tom Cherry had no assistants or anything like that.
He had five or six directors, I guess, because he had Clark Diebel and Wes Donaldson purchasing, Ray Smith, myself, Logan Council, and Clark Diebel.
I don't think I missed anybody.
All right, as you first, you took over then for Bob Rucker.
Yes.
When was that?
That was in, I believe September of, either September or early October of 73.
All right, describe then the campus for which you were responsible, what were its dimensions, and what were the good and bad points
that you had to deal with in terms of realities and who were the key people that you had then reporting to you?
Okay.
In 1973 the basic dimensions of our what we call our public areas that we maintained were really
within the bounds of Texas Avenue, Jersey then, Welbon Road, and University Drive, with exception to the Hensel Park area where we were.
We had some maintenance there.
We had a little bit of maintenance over west of the tracks.
We had
an old creamery building which stood right in the middle of the now entrance to the west campus, the vet school building, the entomology field lab, and I believe that was all.
Yeah, that was all.
One of the biggest problems I had was there had never been any real coordination

between our activities and facilities planning construction and you know I'd come out and there's somebody would be tearing something up and I'd go find out hey what what how when where this kind of thing so finally General Ludeke who was the facilities planning area reported to him he was a vice president he said and Bob had gone to a few of them but he said you know
He said, I think I need you sitting in on my weekly staff meetings on Friday morning, just for coordination.
And that was great.
Sitting in on what?

On Ludicrous, our Ludicrous staff meetings, where I think Joe Adams was director of facilities planning, and I think Paul Stevens, Paul Stevens and Charles Brunt were the other two, one construction, the other one for the design area.
And that got me talking to them on a regular basis, you know, and developing some rapport and all like that.
And finally we got to a point where I was being involved or we were being involved in all the design reviews and all like this so we could provide input.
And it got to a point that they didn't do anything without me

checking with us and all like this but what before that what had happened is that the average working person for grounds average gardener or groundskeeper they would do something and then sit get torn up beyond their control and also with physical we had some problems with physical plant that i had to work through and uh
then before long they would see we could do something and it didn't get torn up, you know, and there began kind of an evolution of change as far as attitudes.
And we were able to get some positions reclassified and where we could move some people up a little bit more according to their abilities.
But I had a staff of Bill Vitapil had then come over as full-time.
I talked to Mr. Cherry about it.
And I think probably in early 1974, he came over as full-time assistant director.
And then B.C.
Hurt was my lead supervisor.
He was over all the new construction, irrigation, and kind of special projects.

Frank Salpatro we hired as, Frank was maybe a foreman or something in the grounds, and he was over all the landscape maintenance, all the mowing, the routine day-to-day housekeeping kind of operations.
And then Albert Engelman, he was over in facilities planning.
And he, um, came over as a supervisor of our roads and pavement section.
And that's something that I had to learn a lot about because I'd never dealt with, with asphalt or paving or anything like that in my prior experience.
Uh, then in, um, I guess it was all also in, in early.
very early 74, that Tom says, you know, you need a number two person.
And Bill wasn't, Bill Vitipa wasn't too interested in that.
He was handling the greenhouse operation, the annual color, and all the setups for special events, commencement, and, you know, that kind of thing.
And so I said, okay.
And I started looking, and then ultimately found Mike Goldwater.
And Mike came to work.
Probably in March or April of 74.
He was in the park system at Arlington, Texas, and had a degree from Texas Tech.
It's one of those things that I had two leading candidates for that.

Both had the same degree, had the same amount of experience, and either one could have done the job, and I guess that's when the good Lord looks after you, you know, and you make the right choice, because Mike was one of these guys that
has knowledge about a little bit of everything.
And we meshed very nicely.
He had a lot of capabilities that I didn't have and I had some that he didn't have.
And we got to a point in our working relationship where we would meet

the hallway going to each other's office with the same thing you know I mean it was it was kind of crazy at times but without him we couldn't have done a lot of what we did because he had the knack of handling a lot of things like that you know
And once we got that set up, we had a very good organization.
We started doing some training.
And by then, I was very familiar with budgets and all like this.
And we had just the state

grounds farm that came in I guess about 1974 probably and that that helped too because that basically helped us set aside a dedicated amount strictly for our grounds and that let us start budgeting for a lot of capital capital outlay equipment equipment and small projects and this kind of thing that above and beyond what the new facilities would

would provide then also in the in the summer of 74 is when when we started all the preparation for the centennial celebration and a firm landscape architectural firm by the name of Mark Newman Dahlberg they did a quote master plan

landscape master plan and then ultimately out of that came six or seven major landscape projects and five street projects or six street projects and we went through probably two years of we had a major landscape project

on the two dormitory areas north and south dorm we had a perimeter entrances project which was the north gate wall which that created lots of consternation particularly among the merchants and you could
You could read through some of their rhetoric.
And they were afraid that we were trying to keep the kids on our side and that the wall was going to have glass embedded in the top and all like that.
And I guess a couple of years after the wall was up, I knew we'd made some headway when I had some kids from the University MYF group at this church.
And we were driving back towards the church, and someone said, you know, that wall doesn't look half bad.
And I thought, boy, we've made some headway there, you know.
But those projects and then a number of street projects, and all that was happening at the same time.
And the campus was just some of the, we had a student draftsman at the time, and
He kept referring to it as DMZ, you know, because of all the fences and all like that.
And in addition to that, we had a number of building projects, had a water line project, you know, and the campus was just torn from A to Z.
What was your evaluation of the master plan which this company provided?
I had some question marks about it.
You know, I mean, it had some good parts.
They didn't understand some things about A&M, you know.

As an example, in the North Durham area, they created a lot of berms and things like this that I said, no, we don't need those out there, because that's where the kids have got to get out and burn off the energy.
And if it's not reasonably usable, they said, well, they can lay out on the sun.
I said, they need to get out and throw a ball around and that kind of stuff.
But I lost that one.
Some of the others we won.
The perimeter and entrances, fortunately, these projects were farmed out to other landscape architects.
Gene Shrickel, Shrickel and Rollins had what we call the North Plaza Mall, which is all the chemistry fountain and all like that.
He and his group were a champ to work with, as well as Hal Stringer,
out of Waco who did the perimeter and entrances, and that was two phases.
One was the wall along University Drive and then the entrance developments at Eastgate and Westgate and South LaSalle.
And we would go to a design review both with the North Plaza Mall and perimeter and entrances.

And then they'd come by the office and we'd get some things worked out on what would really work, you know, and they were very workable, you know, it, uh, and I think those, those projects turned out, turned out very well.
Not that the others didn't, but those probably were because particularly the perimeter and entrances, it gave a definition to the campus and said, okay, here we are.
And we always tried to, from,

1973 or four on is to develop a sense that when a visitor came on campus they got a very positive impression because that's the only time you ever get to make that first impression and it's got to be positive.

And then later, I think in the 80s, and you may remember this, I think the Carnegie Institute came out with a study in maybe the mid-80s, early 80s, that 65 or 70 percent of the entering freshmen choose a school based on appearance, you know.
And that came out and it kind of, I guess, gratified my thoughts about what we were trying to do is providing the

that good first impression, as well as a good exterior environment, because as Bob and I always talked and tried to do, is a lot of the youngsters coming to school, maybe from inner city and this kind of thing, they've never had an opportunity to see a lot of open space and green and this kind of thing.
Did these outside firms spend enough time learning about the campus before they started doing their designs?
I think a few of them did.
I'm not so sure Mark Newman Dahlberg did.
And that's kind of part of the, I know there for a while, landscape architect was a dirty word.
I mean, very seriously, it was a dirty word.
I just said, hey, you know, I'm Director Grounds.
But, no, I think particularly Strickland Rollins and Hal Stringer.
They spent
an inordinate amount of time compared to some of the others.
Like all the streets and roads contracts, that was pretty cut and dried.
We were either replacing, and I know we got to a real problem

when they started on replacing the the existing some of these existing streets on Ross Street because of all the street trees and without the street trees we wouldn't have near the campus that we have today and what we had to do when that that it started down about the architecture building
and went west.
And the facilities planning inspector, his name is George Reisler, he called me and he said, I think we've got a problem.
And went up there and the, they'd done some demolition on the street, removed the curbs, and the live oaks, they had just a proliferation of roots right behind the curbs.
So we got our heads together to decide what
what was the best avenue to do?
We almost knew that we couldn't go in and cut the root.
To put it back exactly where it was, you'd have to cut about 12 inches of the roots off.
That would very seriously damage the trees.
And you can still see it a little bit on Ross Street where the curb goes in, and the streets were narrowed a foot on each side.
And I think that, plus a lot of the preliminary work that we did in the trees, the pruning and thinning,
And I think we probably lost two or three trees out of all those street projects, which I think I'm very proud of that.
All right, so they were sensitive on that issue.
Give some examples in the 70s where the outside designers listened to y'all and heeded some advice.
And then if you remember any examples of where they didn't take your advice.
Hmm.
I'm trying to think where they didn't.
Most of the time they did.
Okay.
We had it, and I can't remember any specifics, but I know early on it took a while.
We couldn't get our comments heard, I think.
One was protection trees and construction areas.
And finally I found out how to do it.
I got it in the Red Book.
And so Mike and I set up and we did a lot of sketches and drawings on preferred and needed tree protection.
They'd come in and slap some two-by-fours around the trunk and call it protected.
And when we were saying you need to go out to the dripland, there's some instances where that was the only protection that could be afforded.
But once we got that in the Red Book, then
we would say, refer to Red Book page, whatever, whatever.
And they say, can't we vary it?
No, you can't.
And then we'd have a contractor that would damage a tree, maybe inadvertently or whatever.
And we had a method of determining damage by the National Arboriculture.
It was an international shade tree conference formula.
And we could put a pretty good cost figure
on that tree based on the kind of tree it was, where it was, the condition of it, and this kind of thing.
And we've collected on it.

And Paul Stevens would say on many occasions, and Paul and I used to argue at length on a number of different things, but he'd say, you better protect those trees or this man will build you real quick.
Looking back from the vantage point of the present,
Should we have varied our tree collection at that point?
Yeah, I think so.
Did anybody suggest it then?
No, and it wasn't until
We started looking at some of that in the mid-80s, I guess, and started doing some, well, maybe the early 80s.
We started doing a lot of, for the first number of years, best of all, we planted live oaks.
And then we got to talking to some of the pathology folks and this kind of thing.
And then that's when we started bringing a lot of other trees.
We were
trying to keep the live oaks primarily as a street tree to make the aesthetic tie between the main campus and west campus.
So that there's a lot of continuity there.
But then we started adding a number of other tree species.
And I think that helped.
And that became more and more evident of the need.
And we did that as a...
you know, as the years went on.
Describe, in general, this whole problem of the live oak decline or whatever it's called.
Well, there's two problems with live oaks and oaks.
First is live oak decline.

Live oak decline is a fairly slow acting disease and it normally attacks a live oak when it has been wounded or and the best correlation I can make to that is like a person that is weakened and they get pneumonia.
It's something very similar.
And it's a fairly slow acting and it's basically a fungal disease that clocks up the water uptake system of the tree, very simply.
And we lost some trees to that, but where we protected them and worked with them, we found that we could keep up the health and that wasn't quite the problem.
that the oak wilt is.
Oak wilt's a different cat.
It's a fairly fast acting tree and it will affect the red oaks and the live oaks.
It affects a broader spectrum of trees.
The live oak decline will also spread by root grounds but the oak decline, or oak wilt I mean, it spreads by
by root grafts and by an insect vector.
Well, the client will spread by an insect vector too because it's a fungus, but the oak wilt is much more easily moved
It's more contagious, I guess you might say.
Why do we appear to have it more on the campus than all throughout the community?
I don't know.
It may have some play that the trees are a little weaker because of compaction, building, sidewalks, that kind of thing.
And there's any number of things that can add up.
to those kind of problems.
But we've got, what, 43 or so thousand people using the campus.
And that creates a problem.
And I've assumed that as we put in new sidewalks, wider walkways, deeper curbs, gutters, and streets, somebody spills some water or they wash out a truck or something or other, all of that
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, we used to try to designate, even going back to the street projects, we had designated places where the concrete trucks could wash out so they could be cleaned up, this kind of thing.
And I think that helped.
We had, I think, a good inspector that he and I got along very good.
We had a good rapport.
And he understood the need for that.
But given where we're located as an institution and a community, what are the special realities that a landscaper has to cope with on that campus?
Oh, we've got a problem with soil and water.
Um, the, um, I think the general soil type is called, um, a Lufkin fine sand.
It's, it's a very,
Compactable material and It if it gets wet and gets any kind of compaction on it's it's the dickens to relieve Makes it very difficult for tree roots particularly to grow.
The other thing is our water.
It's Has a lot of a lot of sodium and bicarbonates particularly sodium and

And that just compounds the compaction problem, because what you do, you tend to increase your pH, go more to the alkaline side, and that tends to what we call deflocculate the soil, which takes out all the air spaces, basically, is what it does.
And that creates another problem.
And that's the reason why we'll go into a drought period like we have now,
And then we'll start getting some real frog stranglers, hopefully.
And that tends to leach out not all the sodium, but a lot of the sodium in the bicarbonates and gets it out of the root zone.
And you start seeing things green up.
And that's one of the reasons.
I mean, we can keep it alive.

with the with our water but ultimately if you had we had the water totally and we didn't get any rainfall we'd start seeing a lot of degeneration of almost all kinds of vegetation because the just water our soil our water has in it now uh relatively good drainage very good drainage is needed um are there some other trees that in hindsight we might have added that would have been a blessing been a
positive to the oak?
Well, we have two or three elms.
The cedar elm, which is a native tree, is a very good tree.
A little leaf elm or an evergreen elm.
depending on where you are and what part of the country you're from, is a good one.
The Chinese pistachio tree I think is an excellent tree.
It's one of the few trees that makes a good fairly fast growing tree and has fall color here, which we desperately need.
The ball cypress is a good tree.
It takes a little establishment
But we used a number of those in like the chemistry mall central campus area.
And those things are up now probably 25, 30 feet tall and have done very well.
But they make a good upland tree.
Once you get them established, you've got to really, really water them for two or three years.
Because if they ever brown, being a conifer, they're
the odds of them coming back are very poor.
But they do make a good upland tree once you get them established.
In that centennial year, were you aware of Dr. Williams' health decline?
I think I had heard some rumors, you know, that he was not feeling well, but I didn't see him all that much.
I mean, I'll tell you, we were so busy back in those days that I went

went to Tom Cherry's staff meetings and any plan reviews and General Ludeke's meeting, and that's about all I did, unless there was some specific request, because we were just trying to keep our heads above water, you know, to keep the campus maintained with everything being so disrupted.
And Dr. Williams going to the hospital and being there a good while didn't have any effect on General Ludeke.
took over as the interim during that time.
Was there any change from your?
Never saw anything.
The only thing we had a change after Tom Cherry retired, and I reported to Clyde Freeman for a year.
That was different.
We seemed to get along OK.
But he was a lot more demanding than Tom Cherry about specifics, on justifications.
Instead of a two or three word paragraph, I had to write two or three paragraphs, that kind of thing.
And I never will forget, Tom Cherry came by to visit me one day after he retired.
And I was needing a large motor grader.
because we had two of them at the time.
And the larger one had just completely worn out.
And I said, you know, I'm having to write a thesis on the justification.
They said, I told you you should have bought the damn thing when I was here.
But other than that, we didn't have that much problem, really.
And then reported to Freeman for about how long?
For about a year.
And then who?
And then Howard Vestal.
became the VP.
Howard took over after Mr. Cherry.
Describe him and his management style.
Howard was a different type of manager.
We got along very good.
We had a very good working relationship.
Um, it's kind of hard to peg the real difference, but he was, had a little more casual, uh, mode about him.
And I would go up to him, you know, I'd have an idea about something and go up to him and it's, Hey, that's what I'm hiring you for.
Do it, you know?
And that's kind of the way we operated.
I always had, um,
Anytime I need to see him, I could get in and see him, as well as Mr. Cherry.
I could call up and say, I need to talk.
And they'd say, come on up.
